headline.main: Where No Business Has Gone Before

results.snippet: Companies are hoping to launch several new spacecraft with money from the government.
results.lead_paragraph: BOULDER, Colo. -- Sitting in a testing facility at the University of Colorado, the inner shell of the Dream Chaser space plane looks like the fuselage of an old DC-3. The test structure has been pushed and pulled to see how it holds up to the stresses and strains of spaceflight. With an additional infusion of money from NASA, the company that makes the Dream Chaser, Sierra Nevada Space Systems, hopes to complete the rest of the structure and eventually take astronauts to orbit.

results.lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (TCM) 31 DAYS OF OSCAR Day 2 of this tribute salutes Jack Nicholson (the most nominated actor: 12 nods and three wins) with four of his best-known films, starting with ''Five Easy Pieces'' (1970), in which he plays a classical pianist who returns to his upper-class family after dropping out of society to work in a California oil field, above. The evening continues with ''Terms of Endearment'' (1983), at 10, for which Mr. Nicholson won the best supporting actor award for his role as a womanizing astronaut who is not as bad as he seems. ''Easy Rider'' (1969) follows at 12:30 a.m., in which he portrays George Hanson, an alcoholic civil rights lawyer who shares a cell with Wyatt and Billy, the motorcyclists played by Peter Fonda and Dennis Hopper. ''The Last Detail'' (1973) is broadcast at 2:15, in which he stars as Buddusky, a Navy lifer who, with his fellow escort (Otis Young), decides to show a young prisoner (Randy Quaid) a good time on his way to the brig. 9 A.M. (Fox News Channel) AMERICA'S NEWSROOM Martha MacCallum talks with David Axelrod, a former senior White House adviser, about the crisis in Egypt, his experience in the White House and his impressions of potential opponents President Obama may face in 2012. The interview will conclude on Thursday.

results.abstract: Astronaut Scott Kelly, twin brother of Rep Gabrielle Giffords's husband and fellow astronaut Mark Kelly, is staying in touch from International Space Station in wake of Tucson shooting that left Giffords severely wounded; photo (M)

headline.main: From Space, Giffords's Brother-in-Law Speaks on Shooting

results.snippet: Scott Kelly, the twin brother of Representative Gabrielle Giffords’s husband, is staying in touch from the International Space Station.
results.lead_paragraph: When Scott Kelly got word from Mission Control on Jan. 8 that the head of the astronaut office wanted to talk with him directly on a private line, he recalled, ''I knew whatever it was, it wasn't good.'' Commander Kelly, who was orbiting the Earth on the International Space Station, knew that private calls from the brass were rare, and that they were rarely about happy things. What he did not know was that his sister-in-law, Representative Gabrielle Giffords, had just been shot in Tucson, and that his twin brother, a fellow astronaut, Mark Kelly, was racing to her side from Houston.

headline.main: Public Drawn to Choice By Giffords's Husband

results.snippet: The astronaut Mark E. Kelly, the husband of Representative Gabrielle Giffords, said he would lead a space shuttle mission in April.

byline.original: By DAN BARRY and JOHN SCHWARTZ; Reporting was contributed by James C. McKinley Jr. from Houston, Marc Lacey and Joseph Goldstein from Tucson, and Sarah Wheaton from New York

results.lead_paragraph: He is going. In the continuing real-life drama that surpasses the most audacious soap opera narrative, the astronaut Mark E. Kelly announced Friday that he would honor his commitment to lead a two-week shuttle mission to the International Space Station -- 200 miles up, and orbiting the earth at 17,500 miles an hour -- while his wife, Representative Gabrielle Giffords, continues her gradual, uncertain recovery from the grievous head wound she suffered during last month's deadly rampage by a gunman in Tucson.

results.abstract: Videotaped messages recovered from a computer at Jared L Loughner's home could mean that a jury will hear from him even though he is unlikely to testify at his trial for Tucson shootings; photos (M)

headline.main: Even if Loughner Doesn't Testify, Jurors Could See Videos, Officials Say

results.snippet: Videotaped messages recovered from a computer at Jared L. Loughner’s home could mean that a jury will hear from him even though he is unlikely to take the stand, officials said.

byline.original: By JOSEPH GOLDSTEIN and MARC LACEY

results.lead_paragraph: TUCSON -- Videotaped messages recovered from a computer at the home of Jared L. Loughner, the man accused of opening fire at a congresswoman's public event in Tucson last month, could mean that a jury will hear from Mr. Loughner in his own words even though he is unlikely to testify at trial, law enforcement officials said. In addition to written statements by Mr. Loughner found at his residence, investigators have retrieved a cache of video recordings in which he expounds on a variety of topics and mentions assassination, a law enforcement official close to the investigation said.

results.abstract: Officials have recently expanded wildlife conservation efforts in a successful effort to boost tourism.

headline.main: On Our Radar: Namibia Designates Entire Coast as National Park

results.snippet: Officials have recently expanded wildlife conservation efforts in a successful effort to boost tourism.
results.lead_paragraph: Namibia designates its entire 976-mile coastline a national park, consolidating several existing preserves into the 26.6 million-acre Namib-Skeleton Coast National Park. The Namibian authorities have recently expanded wildlife conservation efforts in a successful effort to boost tourism; in one notable success, a population of lions has been re-established along the arid Skeleton Coast after being totally extinguished by hunting and poisoning in the 1980s. [The Telegraph]

results.abstract: Cross River Reservoir, home to brown trout, attracts dozens of ice fishermen each winter; photos (M)

headline.main: In the Suburbs, When the Cold Is Biting, and So Are the Fish

results.snippet: In Westchester County, the Cross River Reservoir, home to tasty brown trout, attracts dozens of fishermen at a time this frigid winter.
results.lead_paragraph: Wind cut across the acres of frozen water, as dozens of ice fishermen trudged out at dawn, their astronaut-size waterproof boots fitted with metal spikes for better traction. Some pulled sleds loaded with necessities: food, thermoses and augers to bore holes in the thick ice. Each carried a jigging rod -- a short fishing pole, often less than three feet long for ice fishing -- and a bucket filled with minnows that would conveniently double as a seat as they hunched over a hole no bigger than a saucer waiting for the tug of a fish.

headline.main: Giffords Labors To Speak Again, Even in Lyrics

results.snippet: From mouthing words to speaking, Representative Gabrielle Giffords is on the slow road to recovery.

byline.original: By MARC LACEY and JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.; Marc Lacey reported from Phoenix, and James C. McKinley Jr. from Houston. Denise Grady contributed reporting from New York

results.lead_paragraph: PHOENIX -- Representative Gabrielle Giffords, an eloquent speaker before she was shot in the head last month, is relearning the skill -- progressing from mouthing words and lip-syncing songs to talking briefly by telephone to her brother-in-law in space. With a group of friends and family members acting as a backup chorus, Ms. Giffords has been mouthing the lyrics to ''Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star'' and ''I Can't Give You Anything but Love, Baby.'' And as a surprise for her husband, who is celebrating his birthday this month, a longtime friend who has been helping her through her rehabilitation videotaped her mouthing the words to ''Happy Birthday to You.''

results.abstract: Rep Gabrielle Giffords is relearning to speak, progressing from mouthing words to lip-synching songs to talking briefly on telephone; specialists say it remains unclear what brain functions were affected by traumatic injuries she suffered when she was shot on Jan 8 in Tucson; relatives and friends say that though her recovery is slow and exhausting it is marked by significant progress; photo (M)

results.abstract: Etgar Keret Lives essay on video of an Israeli settler killing a young Palestinian man that was shown online by Israel's largest news portal with advertisements; drawing (M)

headline.main: LIVES: WATCH THE CLIP

results.snippet: Going online for current events, with commercials.
results.lead_paragraph: It's just after midnight on Saturday, and I've been watching images from the protests in Egypt for hours. The TV is on mute, but the raging faces of Cairo are deafening. I don't want my son to wake up, and so I turn off the TV and sit down at my computer. My soccer team, Maccabi Petah Tikva, played Ashdod earlier today, and I surf over to Israel's largest news portal to check the score. On the home page, above the headline reporting Petah Tikva's solid 3-1 victory, the following item appears: ''Palestinian killed in Samaria yesterday. Watch video footage.'' I click on the link. It's not every day that someone offers you the chance to watch a documented killing. The next page says that cameras at an Israeli observation post caught on video a settler shooting a young Palestinian man, after the Palestinian chased him and threw rocks at him. ''Watch the clip.''

results.abstract: New Mexico Gov Susana Martinez wants to privatize Spaceport America--country's first facility built specifically for commercial space travel--saying taxpayers have already paid their fair share and project needs more robust private investment; photos (M)

headline.main: New Mexico's Bet On Space Tourism Stays Earthbound

results.snippet: Gov. Susana Martinez wants to privatize Spaceport America, saying taxpayers have already paid their fair share.
results.lead_paragraph: TRUTH OR CONSEQUENCES, N.M -- Somewhere off a dusty road in southern New Mexico sits a hulking horseshoe-crab-shaped structure and a two-mile-long slab of concrete flanked by mesas and mountains. Welcome to Spaceport America, the country's first facility built specifically for commercial space travel -- an endeavor that the state envisioned as the epicenter of a fledgling industry where tourists would pay large sums to take suborbital flights into space.

results.abstract: Space Shuttle Discovery lifts off on its 39th and final flight heading to International Space Station to deliver supplies, equipment and storage module; photo (M)

headline.main: Discovery, Bound for Space Station, Leaves Earth One Last Time

results.snippet: The 39th mission for the shuttle, with six astronauts aboard, is to deliver supplies, equipment and a storage module to the International Space Station.
results.lead_paragraph: KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. -- With seconds to spare after a last-minute glitch, the repaired shuttle Discovery, grounded since November because of vexing fuel tank cracks, rocketed into orbit Thursday on its 39th and final flight, setting off for the International Space Station to deliver supplies, equipment and a final American storage module. The countdown proceeded smoothly into its final hour, but trouble with an Air Force tracking system computer threw the outcome into doubt. With the countdown holding at the five-minute mark, the Air Force reported a successful repair. The countdown resumed, and Discovery blasted off at 4:53:24 p.m. Eastern time -- three seconds before the end of the day's launching window.
